text:
<@U28TLDP0R> elasticsearch is expensive;
  - can we deploy it in a more minimal way (justin built it but is on something else now, can you look at it on the console)?
 - should we just put it on the ec2 box? (goes away from good cloud practice but it's a decent amount of $)
btw karen is showing some results that card searches are doing pretty well
i'll look at the aws config
much better than decks
if we put it on the ec2 I'll probably have to lower memory / how much shit is cached and things will probably oom once or twice while I'm twiddling
but other than that yeah that's an option
whats our memory utilization running these days
MemoryUtilization 24h
MemoryUtilization 1w
so we're paying $0.372 per Hour for 4 vCPU 32gb ram
max cpu usage is generally beneath 5% with two big spikes that are near 25%
max memory utilization is ~95% but I'm guessing it just uses whatever is available
we apparently have a t2.small es instance sitting around that's probably been slowly eating money, so we should index karen's stuff into it and see how it performs, then either use it or delete it
what do you mean its been sitting around?
its an instance or a reservation?
elasticsearch domains aren't like ec2, they're always running
have we been being charged for elasticsearch each month?
ooh weve had a small es cluster running for a while now/
i guess it was small enough i never noticed it
yeah so if that one performs fine we can just use it
i think thats what we did our first deck indexing test a couple years ago
might be cleaner to blow it away instead
probably, but I'd still like to test it first in case we want slightly bigger or smaller
alright
have karen test it for ya
ok
<@U286Q175Y> what do you think of karen's new time results?
r5.large would be half the memory for half the price
let me try to make this easier
actually, I'm just gonna set up 2 more instances and figure out when these complex queries start hitting breakpoints
